* TODO [#C] Fix README encoding and stale makedir/README  :doc:readme:

*** [low] Top README is Latin-1, shows mojibake on UTF-8 systems (README)
=file= reports =ISO-8859 text=; line 19 contains =Relev\xe9s d'Identit\xe9= (é =
0xE9, Latin-1), which renders as =Relev?s d'Identit?= on a UTF-8 terminal/editor.
Fix: convert to UTF-8 (=iconv -f ISO-8859-1 -t UTF-8 README > README.utf8 && mv=)
and, once the doc toolchain exists, fold this content into =doc/common.org=.
Check other files for the same: =benlib= notes and any source comment headers
with accented author/text may also be Latin-1.

*** [medium] makedir/README documents variables that no longer exist (makedir/README:60-86)
It describes =SUBPROJECT=/=PROGRAMNAME=/=LIBRARYNAME=​= and a =lib/module= layout,
but the actual Makefiles use =MODULES=/=PROGRAMS=/=LIBRARIES=​= plus
=*_OBJECTS=/=*_LIBRARIES=​= (see =bclib/sources/Makefile:92-93=,
=bplib/tests/BpDictTest/sources/Makefile:76-82=). A new user copying README's
names gets nothing built. Rewrite to match the real conventions and add the
items listed in [[file:build-system.issue][build-system]] (two-pass depend, install order, =TARGET=,
default =PREFIX=, =-Werror -pedantic-errors= strictness).

*** [low] Top README is informal and incomplete
It lists the modules but not: how to build/install, the dependency order, the
=PREFIX=/=TARGET= variables, or platform support. Fold into =doc/common.org=
(reading/browsing) once the toolchain exists, keeping a short plain-text README
that points at the generated docs.

** Plan
1. =iconv= the README to UTF-8 (quick win); scan the tree for other Latin-1 files.
2. Rewrite =makedir/README= against the real variable names.
3. Migrate prose into =doc/*.org= per [[file:doc-toolchain-orgmode.issue][doc-toolchain-orgmode]]; leave a thin README.
